<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<LinearLayout xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"
    android:orientation="vertical" android:layout_width="match_parent"
    android:layout_height="match_parent"
    android:padding="16dp">

    <TextView
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:layout_gravity="center_horizontal"
        android:textSize="21sp"
        android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
        android:textStyle="bold"
        android:text="Understanding Task Essence."
        android:paddingBottom="16dp"/>

    <TextView
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:textSize="14sp"
        android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
        android:text="In order to efficiently use Task Essence, you need to understand what Task Essence is. Task Essence is more than an app, it is a philosophy."
        android:paddingBottom="16dp"/>

    <TextView
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:textSize="17sp"
        android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
        android:text="Philosophy"
        android:paddingTop="16dp"
        android:paddingBottom="16dp"/>

    <TextView
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:textSize="14sp"
        android:paddingBottom="16dp"
        android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
        android:text="If you are anything like me, you make long to-do lists that are inevitably lost or forgotten. If the list remains in use, it seems that the items that get checked off are the most simple ones. The list ends up with all the little less-important items completed (such as take out the trash, fill up car with gas, etc.) and the important items (such as complete novel, learn guitar, etc.) go essentially ignored. The reason for this seems to be two-part. First, there is a small amount of joy we get from checking items of a list. Second, it is difficult to focus on and complete large complex tasks. Both of these points push us towards completing the small and often less important tasks." />

    <TextView
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:textSize="14sp"
        android:paddingBottom="16dp"
        android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
        android:text="In a bid to keep my tasks list close and easily accessible, I tried many task list apps. While these were certainly more accessible than a paper list, they seemed to introduce a few new issues. First, they all seemed to have feature overload. While the features certainly have their uses, it does make the app unnecessarily complex and bloated. This ties into the second issue, which is that it takes longer than necessary to enter tasks. So why are these issues? The problem is that it makes us less likely to actually enter tasks." />

    <TextView
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:textSize="14sp"
        android:paddingBottom="16dp"
        android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
        android:text="We can sum up the above paragraphs as follows:" />


    <LinearLayout
        android:layout_width="match_parent"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:orientation="horizontal"
        android:paddingBottom="8dp">

        <TextView
            android:layout_width="wrap_content"
            android:layout_height="wrap_content"
            android:textSize="14sp"
            android:textStyle="bold"
            android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
            android:text="1) "/>

        <TextView
            android:layout_width="wrap_content"
            android:layout_height="wrap_content"
            android:textSize="14sp"
            android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
            android:text="Eliminate unnecessary tasks" />

    </LinearLayout>

    <LinearLayout
        android:layout_width="match_parent"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:orientation="horizontal"
        android:paddingBottom="8dp">

        <TextView
            android:layout_width="wrap_content"
            android:layout_height="wrap_content"
            android:textSize="14sp"
            android:textStyle="bold"
            android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
            android:text="2) " />

        <TextView
            android:layout_width="wrap_content"
            android:layout_height="wrap_content"
            android:textSize="14sp"
            android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
            android:text="Break up large important tasks into smaller tackle-able tasks" />

    </LinearLayout>

    <LinearLayout
        android:layout_width="match_parent"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:orientation="horizontal"
        android:paddingBottom="8dp">

        <TextView
            android:layout_width="wrap_content"
            android:layout_height="wrap_content"
            android:textSize="14sp"
            android:textStyle="bold"
            android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
            android:text="3) " />

        <TextView
            android:layout_width="wrap_content"
            android:layout_height="wrap_content"
            android:textSize="14sp"
            android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
            android:text="Make the app easy to use" />

    </LinearLayout>

    <LinearLayout
        android:layout_width="match_parent"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:orientation="horizontal">

        <TextView
            android:layout_width="wrap_content"
            android:layout_height="wrap_content"
            android:textSize="14sp"
            android:textStyle="bold"
            android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
            android:text="4) " />

        <TextView
            android:layout_width="wrap_content"
            android:layout_height="wrap_content"
            android:textSize="14sp"
            android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
            android:text="Make entering tasks quick" />

    </LinearLayout>

    <TextView
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:textSize="17sp"
        android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
        android:text="Implementation and Use"
        android:paddingTop="16dp"
        android:paddingBottom="16dp"/>

    <TextView
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:textSize="14sp"
        android:paddingBottom="16dp"
        android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
        android:text="Task Essence eliminates unnecessary tasks by limiting the number of tasks that can be entered. It leads you into entering only the tasks that are most important. The number of tasks that can be entered is limited to a maximum of three, and all unfinished tasks will carry over into the next list." />

    <TextView
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:textSize="14sp"
        android:paddingBottom="16dp"
        android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
        android:text="Task Essence also promotes the breaking up of large tasks into smaller more manageable tasks. It accomplishes this by being a daily task list. Therefore you pointed towards entering tasks that can be completed in a single day, which is inherently more manageable. By carrying over unfinished tasks into the next day, you are focused on the tasks that are immediately important." />

    <TextView
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:textSize="14sp"
        android:paddingBottom="16dp"
        android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
        android:text="There are no unnecessary features in Task Essence. This makes it both quick and easy to use. There is no calendar, you do not enter a location or time for each task, no notes, and nothing to distract you from completing your tasks. You may notice that when you enter tasks, your entries are limited in the number of characters that you can enter. This prevents you from entering unnecessarily long entries, and makes you more deliberate in each entry." />

    <TextView
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:textSize="14sp"
        android:paddingBottom="16dp"
        android:textColor="?textColorPrimary"
        android:text="A common use-case, and an example of how I use Task Essence is as follows:" />


    <LinearLayout
        android:layout_width="match_parent"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:orientation="horizontal"
        android:paddingBottom="8dp">

